        "descriptions": [
          {
            "description": "Replication is a cornerstone of cumulative science, providing essential insights into the robustness and generalisability of research findings. Yet, despite an increasing number of published replications, they often fail to affect the belief in, and use of, the original conclusions (Hardwicke et al., 2021). Replications are infrequently cited, often disregarded in theoretical discussions, and\u2014except for striking exceptions\u2014fail to shift research agendas. This raises a critical question: If replications are fundamental to scientific self-correction, why do their results so often fail to shape knowledge?\nIn this proposed study, we will use the FORRT Library of Replication Attempts (FLoRA), which includes ~800 failed replications from across the social and behavioural sciences, to analyse the effect of failed replications on subsequent citations of their target studies. We will fit a Fixed Effects Counterfactual model (FECT) (Liu et al., 2024), a method for causal inference in longitudinal data which combines features of synthetic control and difference-in-difference, to the citation data for studies that have a failed replication in FLoRA, and a sample of control studies.\nIn a second step, we will analyse the treatment effects for individual studies from the FECT model using meta-analytic regression (Viechtbauer, 2025). This will test whether the citation impact of failed replications is moderated by pre-specified characteristics of the replication or the original study (e.g., open-access status, journal rank, author composition or research field).\nIn doing so, this study will (a) estimate the causal effect of failed replications on citation rates of original studies, and (b) identify characteristics that moderate this effect. Understanding what makes some replications more influential than others can inform strategies to increase their visibility and impact.",
            "descriptionType": "Abstract"
          }
        ],
