        "descriptions": [
          {
            "description": "Given the disparity of the results obtained when studying the McGurk effect (See Politzer-Ahles &amp; Pan, 2019; Proverbio et al., 2016), the current study seeks to further investigate the sensitivity of musicians to the McGurk effect. Specifically, I will compare the differences in the rates of accuracy for incongruent audiovisual stimuli between instrument-trained musicians to vocal-trained musicians. The analysis of these distinct groups will lend support to either the original work done by Proverbio and colleagues or the failed replication by Politzer-Ahles and Pan. Recent literature regarding the McGurk effect has sought to determine the robustness and predictability of the effect considering cognitive and perceptual abilities (Basu Mallick et al., 2015; Brown et al., 2018; Getz &amp; Toscano, 2021). Lee and colleagues\u2019 (2024) data showed that musical training was not significantly correlated with susceptibility to the McGurk effect. Hence, I propose that there will not be a substantial difference between the two groups (instrument-trained and vocal-trained musicians) because I believe the effect is more influenced by individual neurodevelopment and functionality than environmental factors.",
            "descriptionType": "Abstract"
          }
        ],
